{
  "texts": [
    "The pioneering work of Akira Fujishima and Kenichi Honda in the late 1960s brought TiO 2 photocatalysis to the forefront by showcasing its ability to split water into hydrogen and oxygen when illuminated by UV light, thereby initiating the exploration of TiO 2 as a photocatalyst for water splitting and pollutant degradation (Kenichi Honda, 2023; Fujishima and Honda, 1972).",
    "TiO 2 photocatalysis has since emerged as a sustainable and ecofriendly strategy for mitigating environmental pollution.",
    "Its ability to mineralize a variety of organic pollutants into harmless byproducts has made it an invaluable tool for wastewater treatment and air purification (Schneider et al., 2014; Dharma et al., 2022).",
    "The ability to harness solar energy for these processes has the potential to revolutionize the energy landscape by offering an environmentally friendly alternative to conventional energy sources (AlSalka et al., 2023; Esrafili et al., 2022; Peiris et al., 2021).",
    "As a result, TiO 2 materials hold immense promise for the generation of clean energy through processes such as photocatalytic hydrogen production and photovoltaic applications."
  ]
}